(44, 7, 26, 43, 15, 17, 18, 'ye are brethren; why do ye wrong', 'Love and Brotherhood Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of loving one another and resolving conflicts. Acts 7:26 highlights the call for unity among brethren, while John 15:17 commands love among followers, even in the face of hatred. This connection highlights the theme of brotherhood and mutual support.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 26, 46, 6, 6, 8, 'ye are brethren; why do ye wrong', 'Conflict Among Brethren', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of conflict among brethren and the call for reconciliation. Acts 7:26 highlights a plea for unity, while 1 Corinthians 6:6-8 addresses disputes that arise among believers, urging them to avoid legal battles.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 27, 42, 12, 14, 14, 'Who made thee a ruler and a judge', 'Judgment and Authority Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the question of authority in judgment. The phrase ''Who made thee a ruler and a judge'' in Acts parallels the inquiry in Luke about being a judge or divider.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 27, 44, 7, 35, 35, NULL, 'Rejection of Moses as Leader', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of Moses by the people, highlighting their question, ''Who made thee a ruler and a judge?'' This connection illustrates the theme of disbelief in God''s chosen leader.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 27, 1, 19, 19, 19, NULL, 'Theme of Deliverance and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of deliverance from danger and the questioning of authority. In Acts, the rejection of a ruler reflects a struggle for safety, while in Genesis, the plea for mercy highlights the urgency of escape from impending doom.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 27, 9, 25, 14, 15, 'Who made thee a ruler', 'Rejection of Authority Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of authority figures. In Acts, a man questions who made Moses a ruler, while in 1 Samuel, Nabal dismisses David''s messengers, showing a similar disregard for leadership.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 27, 20, 9, 7, 8, 'Who made thee a ruler and a judge over us?', 'Rejection of Authority Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejecting authority. In Acts 7:27, the question ''Who made thee a ruler and a judge over us?'' reflects a scornful attitude similar to Proverbs 9:7-8, which warns against reproving a scorner.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 27, 40, 21, 23, 23, 'Who made thee a ruler and a judge over us?', 'Authority and Rejection', 'This connection highlights the challenge to authority present in both passages. In Acts, the question of who has the right to lead is posed, paralleling the inquiry of authority faced by Jesus in Matthew.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 27, 43, 18, 36, 37, 'Who made thee a ruler and a judge over us?', 'Authority and Kingship', 'This connection highlights the challenge of authority in both passages. In Acts, the question of who has the right to rule is posed, while in John, Jesus affirms his kingship but clarifies that his kingdom is not of this world.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 29, 2, 18, 2, 4, 'a stranger in the land of Madian', 'Moses'' Sons and Alien Status', 'Both passages emphasize Moses'' experience as a stranger in a foreign land and mention his two sons. The names of the sons in Exodus reflect his identity as an alien, connecting back to his time in Midian.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 29, 2, 2, 14, 22, 'a stranger in the land of Madian', 'Moses'' Flight to Midian', 'Both passages emphasize Moses'' flight to Midian after killing an Egyptian. They highlight his status as a stranger in a foreign land, which is significant for his identity and future role. This connection underscores the continuity of Moses'' narrative.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 29, 2, 4, 19, 20, 'where he begat two sons', 'Moses'' Journey to Egypt', 'This connection highlights Moses'' transition from Midian to Egypt. Both passages emphasize his role as a father and leader, as he returns with his sons to fulfill God''s command.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 30, 2, 3, 1, 2, 'an angel of the Lord in a flame of fire', 'Moses and the Burning Bush', 'Both passages emphasize the appearance of ''the angel of the Lord in a flame of fire'' to Moses, highlighting a significant moment in his calling. The connection illustrates the continuity of God''s communication with Moses in both the wilderness and at Horeb.', 'parallel', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 30, 23, 43, 2, 2, 'flame of fire', 'Connection of Fire Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of God in fire. Acts 7:30 describes an angel in a flame of fire, while Isaiah 43:2 assures protection through fire without being burned.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 30, 44, 7, 35, 35, 'angel of the Lord in a flame of fire in a bush', 'Moses and Divine Calling', 'This connection highlights the role of Moses as a chosen leader. Both passages emphasize the divine encounter with the angel in the bush.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 30, 23, 63, 9, 9, 'angel of the Lord', 'Affliction and Divine Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of an angel in times of affliction. Acts 7:30 describes an angel appearing to Moses, while Isaiah 63:9 speaks of the angel of his presence saving and redeeming during affliction.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 30, 1, 22, 15, 18, 'angel of the Lord', 'Divine Communication through Angels', 'This connection highlights the role of the angel of the Lord in both passages. In Acts, the angel appears in a flame of fire, while in Genesis, the angel speaks to Abraham, emphasizing divine guidance and communication.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 30, 1, 48, 15, 16, 'Angel of the Lord', 'Connection of Divine Presence', 'This connection highlights the presence of the ''Angel'' in both passages. In Acts, the ''angel of the Lord'' appears in a miraculous form, while in Genesis, the ''Angel which redeemed me'' signifies God''s active role in Joseph''s life.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 30, 2, 7, 7, 7, 'forty years were expired', 'Moses'' Age and Divine Encounter', 'This connection highlights the timeline of Moses'' life, noting that he was ''fourscore years old'' when he confronted Pharaoh, which aligns with the ''forty years'' mentioned in the SOURCE verse, indicating a significant period of preparation before his mission. Both passages emphasize the pivotal moments in Moses'' life that shaped his leadership.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 31, 2, 3, 3, 4, 'wondered at the sight', 'Moses'' Encounter with God', 'Both passages emphasize Moses'' response to the divine sight. In Acts, Moses ''wondered at the sight,'' paralleling his decision to ''turn aside'' in Exodus to witness the burning bush.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 32, 2, 3, 6, 6, 'I am the God of thy fathers', 'Divine Encounter with Moses', 'Both passages emphasize God''s declaration as the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, which establishes His authority and covenant relationship. Additionally, Moses'' fear in both instances highlights the profound impact of encountering the divine.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 32, 40, 22, 32, 32, NULL, 'God of the Living', 'Both passages emphasize God''s relationship with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob. This connection highlights the continuity of God''s covenant with the living, contrasting with the idea of death.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 32, 1, 28, 13, 17, 'Then Moses trembled, and durst not behold', 'Divine Presence and Fear', 'Both passages emphasize the fear and reverence experienced by individuals in the presence of God. In Acts, Moses trembles at God''s declaration, while Jacob expresses fear upon realizing he is in a sacred place.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
